Feb 1512":"17 February 1512","Whitehill, Rufford, West Lancashire district, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","Whytehill, , Durham, England":"Durham, England","Whitewell, Durham":"Whitewell, County Westmeath, Ireland","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Millot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Leonce, Aime, Aubert, Celine, Herve, Julien, Leandre, Marcel, Monique, Patrice, Raymonde, Roussel.","French and Catalan: metonymic occupational name for a grower or seller of millet or panic grass, or a topographic name for someone who lived by a field of millet, from French and Catalan <i>millet</i> (from Latin <i>milietum</i>, a derivative of <i>milium</i>, in Old French <i>mil</i> ‘millet’).","French: habitational name from (Le) Millet, the name of several places in various parts of France."],"variants":[{"name":"Miles","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Mile</i> + genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, or from its other Old French form <i>Miles</i>, a derivative of ancient Germanic <i>Milo</i>, based on the element <i>mil</i>, from <i>mel</i> ‘good, generous’. The Old French oblique case form was <i>Milon</i> (see   Milon   1). Compare   Millen   and   Millson  .","English: variant, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, of   Myhill  , from a vernacular form of the Biblical name   Michael  . <i>Miles</i> Coverdale, the translator of the Bible, when in Germany, called himself <i>Michael</i> Anglus (‘the Englishman’).","Irish (Louth and Kilkenny): when not the same as 1 or 2, it is sometimes an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maolmhuire</b>, see   Myles  ."]},{"name":"Millett","meanings":["English: variant of   Millet  .","Irish (Tipperary, Galway and Mayo): from <b>Míolóid</b> or its variant <b>Méalóid</b>, a byname based on Latin <i>miles</i>, <i>militis</i> ‘soldier’."]},{"name":"Millette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Jacques, Adelard, Andre, Aurore, Camille, Gilles, Jean Noel, Lucien, Monique, Normand.","Altered form of French   Millet  , reflecting the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>. Compare   Meyette  ."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Lorraine   or variant spelling of   Laurie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lorraine","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin denoting a migrant from the province of <i>Lorraine</i> in eastern France. This derives its name from Latin <i>Lotharingia</i> ‘territory of the people of <i>Lothar</i>’. The latter is a Germanic personal name derived from <i>hlud</i> ‘fame’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. <i>Lorraine</i> began to be used as a girl's name in Scotland in the 19th century, and for a time in the second half of the 20th century enjoyed great popularity, which has since waned."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Ralph Millot was born in 1473, in Durham, England, his father, Robert Millot, was 27 and his mother, Joan Millot, was 24. He married Isabel Eure in 1494, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 17 February 1512, in Whitewell, County Westmeath, Ireland, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1473–17 Feb 1512":"1473–17. veebruar 1512","1473–1512":"1473–1512","1462–1535":"1462–1535","1496–1553":"1496–1553","1446–1512":"1446–1512","1450–1512":"1450–1512","1535":"1535","1446":"1446","1512":"1512","1553":"1553","1496":"1496","1473":"1473","1462":"1462","1494":"1494","1450":"1450","17 Feb 1512":"17. veebruar 1512","Whitehill, Rufford, West Lancashire district, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","Whytehill, , Durham, England":"Durham, England","Whitewell, Durham":"Whitewell, County Westmeath, Iirimaa","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1473–17 Feb 1512":"1473–17. helmikuuta 1512","1473–1512":"1473–1512","1462–1535":"1462–1535","1496–1553":"1496–1553","1446–1512":"1446–1512","1450–1512":"1450–1512","1535":"1535","1446":"1446","1512":"1512","1553":"1553","1496":"1496","1473":"1473","1462":"1462","1494":"1494","1450":"1450","17 Feb 1512":"17. helmikuuta 1512","Whitehill, Rufford, West Lancashire district, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","Whytehill, , Durham, England":"Durham, England","Whitewell, Durham":"Whitewell, County Westmeath, Irlanti","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1473–17 Feb 1512":"1473–17 février 1512","1473–1512":"1473–1512","1462–1535":"1462–1535","1496–1553":"1496–1553","1446–1512":"1446–1512","1450–1512":"1450–1512","1535":"1535","1446":"1446","1512":"1512","1553":"1553","1496":"1496","1473":"1473","1462":"1462","1494":"1494","1450":"1450","17 Feb 1512":"17 février 1512","Whitehill, Rufford, West Lancashire district, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, Angleterre","Whytehill, , Durham, England":"Durham, Angleterre","Whitewell, Durham":"Whitewell, County Westmeath, Irlande","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Lord Ralph Millot est né en 1473, à Durham, Angleterre, son père, Robert Millot, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Joan Millot,